***

## Why this project exists

Students often handle limited allowance, part-time income, hostel fees, transport costs, food purchases, academic materials, and occasional lifestyle spending all within a tight budget. Student expense tracking systems are typically designed to make these categories visible, reduce overspending, and encourage better monthly control. [1][2][3]

This project turns that need into a cleaner web workflow with separate spaces for monitoring, planning, and reviewing finances. Instead of combining everything in one cluttered screen, the app distributes tasks into focused pages that reflect how finance dashboards and expense trackers are often organized. [10][11][12]

***

## Core Features

<div align="center">
  <img src="https://readme-typing-svg.demolab.com?font=Instrument+Sans&weight=600&size=20&pause=800&color=2D6A4F&center=true&vCenter=true&width=900&lines=Dashboard+Overview;Transaction+Management;Budget+Planning;Savings+Goal+Tracking;Analytics+%26+Insight+Cards" alt="Features Animation" />
</div>

- Separate pages for home, dashboard, transactions, budgets, goals, and analytics. [4][6]
- Dashboard cards for total income, expenses, balance, and savings rate. [11][12]
- Transaction input flow for income and expense records. [4][6]
- Budget planning section for category-wise monthly controls. [1][10]
- Goal tracking section for planned savings targets. [2][12]
- Analytics page for summary-style financial review. [10][11]
- Responsive finance-style UI with theme toggle support. [13][5]

***

## Page Map

| Page | Role | What it does |
|------|------|--------------|
| `index.html` | Entry point | Introduces the project and routes users to all key sections |
| `dashboard.html` | Summary page | Shows income, expenses, savings rate, balance, and charts [11][12] |
| `transactions.html` | Activity page | Adds and manages transaction records [4][6] |
| `budgets.html` | Planning page | Stores category budget values and shows current budget blocks [1][10] |
| `goals.html` | Savings page | Creates and displays savings goals [2][12] |
| `analytics.html` | Insights page | Displays financial totals and insight summaries [10][11] |

***

## Folder Structure

```bash
student-expense-tracker/
│
├── index.html
├── dashboard.html
├── transactions.html
├── budgets.html
├── goals.html
├── analytics.html
│
├── css/
│   ├── common.css
│   ├── index.css
│   ├── dashboard.css
│   ├── transactions.css
│   ├── budgets.css
│   ├── goals.css
│   └── analytics.css
│
└── js/
    ├── common.js
    ├── index.js
    ├── dashboard.js
    ├── transactions.js
    ├── budgets.js
    ├── goals.js
    └── analytics.js
```

This file organization keeps shared design and layout logic centralized while allowing each screen to hold its own dedicated styles and behavior. That modular separation is commonly used in front-end finance trackers because it improves readability and future extension. [4][5][6]

***

## User Workflow

### 1. Start from Home
The user lands on the home page and moves to the required section through direct navigation links.

### 2. Add money activity
The transactions page is used to enter income or expense items with details such as amount, category, date, and note. Transaction entry is the core data layer in most expense tracker applications because reporting depends on these records. [4][10]

### 3. Define category limits
The budgets page allows monthly amount planning for categories like food, transport, books, hostel, entertainment, and shopping. Category-based planning is a common feature in budgeting tools because it helps users compare real spending against intended spending. [1][10]

### 4. Track financial goals
The goals page helps students monitor savings targets such as gadgets, trips, semester supplies, or emergency funds. Savings-goal support is frequently used in student-facing finance apps because it links current spending discipline to future purchases. [2][12]

### 5. Review summary and insights
The dashboard and analytics pages provide overview-style reading through cards, charts, and summary blocks, which is a standard finance-dashboard pattern for quick understanding. [13][11][12]

***

## Tech Stack

| Technology | Use |
|-----------|-----|
| HTML5 | Structure and page layout |
| CSS3 | Styling, responsiveness, theming |
| JavaScript | Form logic, calculation, DOM rendering |
| Chart.js | Data visualization and dashboard charts [14][11] |
| Google Fonts | Better typography presentation |

***

## Design Notes

- Clean dashboard-inspired layout.
- Separate workflow pages instead of one cluttered file.
- Shared common stylesheet for consistency.
- Individual page stylesheets for easier customization.
- Light and dark theme support.
- Presentation-friendly structure for college submission or portfolio use.

Modern finance dashboard examples often rely on card layouts, summary blocks, charts, and strong separation between overview and action pages, which aligns with this design direction. [13][11][15]

***

## Current State

This version intentionally starts **without demo data**, so the interface remains empty until real user input is added. Expense trackers commonly produce meaningful summaries only after transactions, budgets, or goals are entered, so empty-state behavior is normal in early versions or front-end prototypes. [16][2][11]

The current structure is suitable for:
- College mini-projects
- UI prototypes
- Front-end portfolio projects
- Firebase or localStorage extension later

***

## Future Improvements

- Add `localStorage` for persistence across pages.
- Add Firebase Auth and Firestore.
- Add export to CSV or PDF.
- Add recurring bills and reminders.
- Add filters by week, month, and category.
- Add better analytics and growth charts.
- Add student-focused smart recommendations based on category trends. Student finance tools increasingly include simplified recommendations and behavioral guidance as part of their value. [3][12]

***

## Setup

### Clone the repository
```bash
git clone <your-repository-url>
```

### Open the project folder
```bash
cd student-expense-tracker
```

### Run the website
Open `index.html` directly in the browser or use the VS Code Live Server extension for a smoother multi-page development workflow.

